:"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3667"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8746"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15691/tags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15691/relationships/tags"}},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45589"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45590"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45591"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45592"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15691/contributions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15691/relationships/contributions"}}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"120431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120431"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of profuse watery diarrhoea and vomiting. Her mother reports she has had eight to ten large-volume watery stools per day without blood or mucus. The diarrhoea has continued despite withholding food for the past 12 hours. She attends childcare where several other children have been unwell with similar symptoms. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. Her immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly dehydrated with dry mucous membranes. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft with increased bowel sounds but no tenderness or masses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is the most likely cause of her diarrhoea?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clostridium difficile","Entamoeba histolytica","Giardia lamblia","Lactobacillus species","Rotavirus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with acute gastroenteritis characterised by profuse watery diarrhoea that persists despite fasting, consistent with secretory diarrhoea. The presence of similar cases in her childcare centre suggests an infectious outbreak. In children under five years, rotavirus is the most common cause of severe diarrhoea worldwide and typically presents with this clinical picture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotavirus\u003C/strong\u003E causes secretory diarrhoea by disrupting sodium-glucose cotransport and activating the enteric nervous system, leading to increased chloride secretion and decreased sodium absorption. The virus directly damages enterocytes and triggers the release of neurotransmitters that alter ion transport. The characteristic features include profuse watery diarrhoea, vomiting, and fever, with symptoms typically lasting 3-8 days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClostridium difficile\u003C/strong\u003E causes inflammatory diarrhoea through toxin-mediated mucosal damage and is typically associated with recent antibiotic use, which is not present in this case. The diarrhoea is often bloody or contains mucus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEntamoeba histolytica\u003C/strong\u003E causes amoebic dysentery characterised by bloody diarrhoea with mucus, abdominal pain, and tenesmus. It is uncommon in Australian children and typically associated with travel to endemic areas - which has not occurred in this case. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiardia lamblia\u003C/strong\u003E causes chronic diarrhoea through malabsorption rather than secretion. The diarrhoea is typically foul-smelling and fatty (steatorrhoea), and symptoms develop over weeks rather than days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactobacillus species\u003C/strong\u003E are normal gut flora that help maintain intestinal health and do not cause diarrhoea. They are often used as probiotics to help restore normal gut flora after gastroenteritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rotavirus is the most common cause of severe diarrhoea in children under five years worldwide, causing secretory diarrhoea through disruption of intestinal ion transport","Secretory diarrhoea persists despite fasting and is characterised by large-volume watery stools without blood or mucus"],"references":["DuPont HL. Persistent Diarrhea: A Clinical Review. JAMA. 2016 Jun 28;315(24):2712-23. doi: 10.1001/jama.2016.7833. PMID: 27357241","Nemeth V, Pfleghaar N. Diarrhea. [Updated 2022 Nov 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448082/","Kaiser L, Surawicz CM. Infectious causes of chronic diarrhoea. Best Pract Res Clin Gastroenterol. 2012 Oct;26(5):563-71. doi: 10.1016/j.bpg.2012.11.001. PMID: 23384802","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"102025"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120431/itemRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120431/relationships/itemRevision"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22744"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120431/question","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120431/relationships/question"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120431/stemMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120431/relationships/stemMedia"}},"explanationMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120431/explanationMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120431/relationships/explanationMedia"}}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"102025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/102025"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-10-15T18:30:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-10-15T18:31:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15691"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/102025/item","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/102025/relationships/item"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"120431"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/102025/content","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/102025/relationships/content"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9/group","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9/relationships/group"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9/heading","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9/relationships/heading"}},"ancestors":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9/ancestors","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9/relationships/ancestors"}},"parents":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9/parents","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9/relationships/parents"}},"children":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.c